  doi = {10.1128/MCB.00227-08},
  abstract = {The myocyte enhancer factor 2 (MEF2) transcription factors play important roles in neuronal, cardiac, and skeletal muscle tissues. MEF2 serves as a nuclear sensor, integrating signals from several signaling cascades through protein-protein interactions with kinases, chromatin remodeling factors, and other transcriptional regulators. Here, we report a novel interaction between the catalytic subunit of protein phosphatase 1\ensuremath{\alpha} (PP1\ensuremath{\alpha}) and MEF2. Interaction occurs within the nucleus, and binding of PP1\ensuremath{\alpha} to MEF2 potently represses MEF2-dependent transcription. The interaction utilizes uncharacterized domains in both PP1\ensuremath{\alpha} and MEF2, and PP1\ensuremath{\alpha} phosphatase activity is not obligatory for MEF2 repression. Moreover, a MEF2-PP1\ensuremath{\alpha} regulatory complex leads to nuclear retention and recruitment of histone deacetylase 4 to MEF2 transcription complexes. PP1\ensuremath{\alpha}-mediated repression of MEF2 overrides the positive influence of calcineurin signaling, suggesting PP1\ensuremath{\alpha} exerts a dominant level of control over MEF2 function. Indeed, PP1\ensuremath{\alpha}-mediated repression of MEF2 function interferes with the prosurvival effect of MEF2 in primary hippocampal neurons. The PP1\ensuremath{\alpha}-MEF2 interaction constitutes a potent locus of control for MEF2-dependent gene expression, having potentially important implications for neuronal cell survival, cardiac remodeling in disease, and terminal differentiation of vascular, cardiac, and skeletal muscle.},
