  abstract = {Background: Epidemiological and preclinical studies suggest that mental activity levels may alter dementia risk. Two critical remaining issues for the area of cognitive training in late life are: a) the persistence of effect over extended follow-up and b) transfer of effect to non-trained domains. The aim of this report was to therefore systematically review results from clinical trials which have examined the effect of cognitive exercise on longitudinal cognitive performance in healthy elderly individuals. Methods: MEDLINE, PubMed and key references were used to generate an initial list of relevant studies (N = 54). These were reviewed to identify randomized controlled trials which tested the effect of a discrete cognitive training regime on longitudinal (\ensuremath{>}3 months) post-training neuropsychological performance in healthy older adults. Seven RCTs met entry criteria. Pre- and post- change scores were integrated using a random effects weighted mean difference (WMD) meta-analytic approach (Review Manager Version 4.2). Results: A strong effect size was observed for cognitive exercise interventions compared to wait-and-see control conditions (WMD = 1.07, CI: 0.32-1.83, z = 2.78, n = 7, p = 0.006, N = 3194). RCTs with follow-up greater than 2 years did not appear to produce lower effect size estimates than those with less extended follow-up. Quality of reporting of trials was in general low. Conclusions: Systematic review of cognitive training in healthy older individuals found strong and persistent protective effects on longitudinal neuropsychological performance. Transfer of these effects to dementia-relevant domains such as general cognition and daily functioning has been reported in some studies. Importantly, cognitive training has yet to be shown to prevent incident dementia in an appropriately designed trial and this is now an international priority.},
