  issn = {1471-2202},
  doi = {10.1186/1471-2202-13-155},
  abstract = {BACKGROUND: \ensuremath{\beta}-amyloid (A\ensuremath{\beta}) accumulation is described as a hallmark of Alzheimer's disease (AD). A\ensuremath{\beta} perturbs a number of synaptic components including nicotinic acetylcholine receptors containing \ensuremath{\alpha}7 subunits (\ensuremath{\alpha}7-nAChRs), which are abundantly expressed in the hippocampus and found on GABAergic interneurons. We have previously demonstrated the existence of a novel, heteromeric \ensuremath{\alpha}7\ensuremath{\beta}2-nAChR in basal forebrain cholinergic neurons that exhibits high sensitivity to acute A\ensuremath{\beta} exposure. To extend our previous work, we evaluated the expression and pharmacology of \ensuremath{\alpha}7\ensuremath{\beta}2-nAChRs in hippocampal interneurons and their sensitivity to A\ensuremath{\beta}.
RESULTS: GABAergic interneurons in the CA1 subregion of the hippocampus expressed functional \ensuremath{\alpha}7\ensuremath{\beta}2-nAChRs, which were characterized by relatively slow whole-cell current kinetics, pharmacological sensitivity to dihydro-\ensuremath{\beta}-erythroidine (DH\ensuremath{\beta}E), a nAChR \ensuremath{\beta}2* subunit selective blocker, and \ensuremath{\alpha}7 and \ensuremath{\beta}2 subunit interaction using immunoprecipitation assay. In addition, \ensuremath{\alpha}7\ensuremath{\beta}2-nAChRs were sensitive to 1 nM oligomeric A\ensuremath{\beta}. Similar effects were observed in identified hippocampal interneurons prepared from GFP-GAD mice.
CONCLUSION: These findings suggest that A\ensuremath{\beta} modulation of cholinergic signaling in hippocampal GABAergic interneurons via \ensuremath{\alpha}7\ensuremath{\beta}2-nAChRs could be an early and critical event in A\ensuremath{\beta}-induced functional abnormalities of hippocampal function, which may be relevant to learning and memory deficits in AD.},
